, educational, and cultural roles. The book includes a wealth of examples detailing the Sufi experience. Contributors use Arabic, Persian, Indian, Central Asian, and Ottoman sources and employ approaches grounded in history, sociology, psychology, anthropology, religious studies, and literary analysis. This is an illuminating work, showing how ordinary Muslims, Muslim notables, Sufis, legal scholars, and rulers have perceived both themselves and the world around them through the prism of dreams and visions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aPsychology : Dreams. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Islam. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Sufism. 7aRELIGION / Islam / Sufi.2bisacsh1 aAlexandrin, Elizabeth R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBashir, Shahzad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelek, Özgen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFelek, Özgen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGhaemmaghami, Omid, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagen, Gottfried, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Jonathan G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhan, Fareeha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhanna, Meenakshi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKinberg, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnysh, Alexander D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnysh, Alexander D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMancini-Lander, Derek J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l